  "prompt": "Which is stronger acid, HClO4 or HIO4? And why?",
  "response": "**Perchloric acid (HClO4)** is a stronger acid than **periodic acid (HIO4)**. Here's why:\n\n1. **Electronegativity of the central atom**: Chlorine (Cl) is more electronegative than iodine (I). The greater electronegativity of Cl draws electron density away from the oxygen atoms in HClO4, making the O-H bond more polar and easier to break, thereby increasing the acidity.\n\n2. **Oxidation state and stability of the conjugate base**: In both HClO4 and HIO4, the central atom (Cl or I) is in the +7 oxidation state. However, the conjugate base of HClO4, ClO4^\u2212 (perchlorate ion), is more stabilized by resonance and the higher electronegativity of Cl compared to IO4^\u2212 (periodate ion), the conjugate base of HIO4. A more stable conjugate base means the acid is more willing to donate a proton, making HClO4 a stronger acid.\n\n3. **Bond strength**: The H-O bond in HClO4 is weaker than in HIO4 because Cl is smaller and more electronegative, leading to a stronger attraction to the electrons in the O-H bond and making it easier for the proton to dissociate.\n\nThus, **HClO4 is a stronger acid than HIO4** due to the greater electronegativity of Cl, the increased stability of its conjugate base, and the weaker H-O bond.",
